# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:24:59
overview:<p>The Pacifier is a 30-ton SecurityMech designed by Alshain Weapons for civilian law enforcement within the Draconis Combine. Introduced in 3038, the design was developed after the Combine had previously relied on imported quadrupedal Guard SecurityMechs of Capellan manufacture for its domestic policing needs. Alshain Weapons created the Pacifier as a domestically produced alternative that could serve both police and light combat roles, though the company's notorious lack of quality control earned the design an unfavorable reputation from the outset. Despite these shortcomings, the Pacifier proved its worth during the Clan Invasion and Jihad, where its pilots fought against far superior foes and forced a reassessment of the design's value. By the early thirty-first century, the Pacifier had become one of the most recognized SecurityMech designs in the Inner Sphere, mentioned in the same breath as the Copper, Guard, and Inquisitor.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Pacifier is built on an Alshain Type 40-30L IndustrialMech chassis and powered by a Hermes 90 fuel cell engine, giving it a modest top speed of only 32 kph. This slow speed is the design's most significant tactical limitation, restricting it to static defense, checkpoint duty, and urban patrol where rapid redeployment is not required. Three single heat sinks manage the minimal heat load generated by its ballistic and missile weaponry, while standard industrial armor provides basic protection against small arms fire. The conspicuous absence of an ejection seat in the original model was a frequent point of criticism, leaving pilots trapped in a disabled machine.</p><p>Where the Pacifier distinguishes itself from lighter SecurityMechs is its unusually diverse weapons suite. A Thunderstroke-L LRM-5 in the left torso provides standoff engagement capability rare among SecurityMechs, while a Telos-2 SRM-2 in the right torso handles close-range work. Both launchers can fire tear gas rounds for crowd dispersal or standard munitions for genuine combat. Each arm mounts a Sperry Browning machine gun and a sprayer, the latter serving double duty for both riot suppression and firefighting operations. An advanced fire control system ties the entire weapons suite together, giving the Pacifier accuracy that compensates somewhat for its limited mobility. This combination of missile, ballistic, and utility systems makes the Pacifier one of the most versatile SecurityMech platforms available, capable of transitioning from firefighting to riot control to light combat without reconfiguration.</p>

deployment:<p>Developed in the 3080s, the CCU-40 serves as a comprehensive upgrade addressing the original Pacifier's most criticized shortcomings. Heavy industrial armor replaces the standard plate, substantially improving survivability, and an ejection seat finally gives pilots a means of escape from a disabled machine. The weapons suite has been modernized: the LRM-5 and SRM-2 are replaced by twin MML-3 launchers with two tons of ammunition, allowing each launcher to fire either long-range or short-range missiles as the tactical situation demands and providing up to six missiles per volley. Light machine guns replace the standard models, while the sprayers are retained for their proven riot control and firefighting utility. This variant reflects lessons learned from decades of service and validates the Pacifier concept that Alshain Weapons' original quality failures had nearly discredited.</p>

history:<p>The Pacifier's origins lie in the Draconis Combine's dissatisfaction with relying on foreign-built SecurityMechs for domestic law enforcement. Prior to 3038, Combine civilian authorities had employed the Capellan-manufactured Guard, a cheap but crude quadrupedal design. Alshain Weapons was tasked with developing a domestically produced SecurityMech that could serve the Combine's police forces without depending on Capellan imports. The resulting CCU-36 Pacifier offered substantially more capability than the Guard, but Alshain Weapons' poor quality control immediately undermined the design's reputation.</p><p>The combination of shoddy manufacturing and the lack of an ejection seat made the Pacifier deeply unpopular with its intended operators. Most units were relegated to the lowest-priority planetary militia postings, where they served as little more than armed scarecrows for minor civil disturbances. This ignominious status persisted for decades, with the Pacifier regarded as a design nobody wanted to pilot and few commanders wanted in their formations.</p><p>The Clan Invasion of 3049 changed the Pacifier's fortunes dramatically. When the Clans struck the Combine's border worlds, every available armed machine was pressed into service, including scores of Pacifiers that their militia pilots had never expected to take into real combat. Against overwhelming Clan forces, Pacifier crews fought with a desperation and tenacity that surprised observers on both sides, and the design's diverse weapons suite proved more useful in irregular warfare than its critics had anticipated. The Jihad further reinforced this reassessment, as Pacifier units again found themselves in combat roles far beyond their design specifications. These experiences led to a fundamental reevaluation of the Pacifier's capabilities and ultimately drove the development of the upgraded CCU-40 model in the 3080s, which addressed the original's most glaring deficiencies while preserving its proven weapons flexibility.</p>

